article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw scored 24 points and Stacey Dales-Schuman added 18 as the host Washington Mystics topped the Charlotte Sting 68-60 Thursday. It was the first time this season Washington has won two straight.
article.headline: Half of Washington's wins are vs. Charlotte
article.linkText: Hapless Mystics top strong Sting for 2nd straight win
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Mystics finally have a winning streak.

Chamique Holdsclaw scored 24 points and Stacey Dales-Schuman added 18 as the Mystics won their second straight game with a 68-60 victory over the Charlotte Sting on Thursday.

Washington (4-14) has won two straight for the first time this season, while Charlotte had its four-game winning streak snapped. Two of Washington's wins this season have come against Charlotte (12-7), which entered the game atop the Eastern Conference.

"It means a big deal to us," Dales-Schuman said. "This is a very good Charlotte team, and if we can play with a team like Charlotte, then we can play with anybody."

Allison Feaster led the Sting with 18 points, and Tammy Sutton-Brown added 11.

Dales-Schuman made three 3-pointers during a 20-2 run that gave Washington a 58-45 lead with under six minutes left. She has struggled with her shooting all season.

"Since the first game, we've been waiting for her to break out again," Washington coach Marianne Stanley said. "People kept feeding her, and she kept making shots."

Coco Miller also helped the Mystics by scoring 10 of her 14 points in the second half.

Charlotte led throughout the first half and had a 25-17 lead with about nine minutes remaining. But the Mystics slowly crept back and tied it at 32 at halftime.

The Mystics also took advantage of 17 Charlotte turnovers, converting them into 21 points.

"(The Mystics) are starting to play better," Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey said. "I think they have a lot more confidence, they are playing more aggressively and they are attacking the basket more."
